We use a binary score of

00:10:00.320 --> 00:10:01.760
does a package have it or not?

00:10:02.559 --> 00:10:03.840
And we spend far too much

00:10:03.840 --> 00:10:05.200
and there's many hours of my life

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:06.559
that I won't get back of thinking,

00:10:06.559 --> 00:10:07.599
well, but a package might have

00:10:07.599 --> 00:10:09.599
two vignettes or three vignettes

00:10:09.599 --> 00:10:10.559
or it might have a vignette

00:10:10.559 --> 00:10:11.919
that's only one page

00:10:11.919 --> 00:10:13.760
or four pages or five pages.

00:10:16.719 --> 00:10:18.479
And it really just doesn't matter.

00:10:18.479 --> 00:10:20.239
You know, you're sort of quibbling of,

00:10:20.799 --> 00:10:22.239
out of all the packages,

00:10:22.239 --> 00:10:23.760
most of them don't really have vignettes

00:10:23.760 --> 00:10:24.960
and those are the ones that you care about.

00:10:24.960 --> 00:10:26.080
The rest are just,

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:27.359
okay, two vignettes is better

00:10:27.359 --> 00:10:28.960
than one vignette, but you know.

00:10:28.960 --> 00:10:29.919
But again, you could change it,

00:10:29.919 --> 00:10:31.119
but that's the sort of,

00:10:31.119 --> 00:10:32.000
getting into that mindset

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:33.200
of what you're trying to capture.

00:10:35.280 --> 00:10:36.640
And I told you I would disagree, you know.

00:10:36.640 --> 00:10:38.320
So people will come up to me afterwards

00:10:38.320 --> 00:10:39.280
and say, oh, no, no, no,

00:10:39.280 --> 00:10:39.840
you should do that.

00:10:40.799 --> 00:10:42.559
Dependencies, how big is an imports list?

00:10:42.559 --> 00:10:43.679
You know, how many dependencies

00:10:43.679 --> 00:10:44.799
in a package, right?

00:10:45.520 --> 00:10:46.400
We could argue that.

00:10:47.039 --> 00:10:49.039
And there's a podcast that I listen to

00:10:49.039 --> 00:10:50.000
that always asks,

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:51.039
it's called More or Less,

00:10:51.039 --> 00:10:52.000
great podcast,

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:53.200
and it always asks the question,

00:10:53.200 --> 00:10:54.239
is that a big number?

00:10:54.799 --> 00:10:55.760
As if I said a package

00:10:55.760 --> 00:10:57.039
has got 10 dependencies,

00:10:57.599 --> 00:10:59.039
is that a big number?

00:10:59.039 --> 00:11:00.080
Is 10 big?

00:11:00.080 --> 00:11:00.880
It might be big.

00:11:00.880 --> 00:11:01.919
Is 20 big?

00:11:01.919 --> 00:11:02.960
What about two?

00:11:02.960 --> 00:11:03.520
I don't know.

00:11:05.919 --> 00:11:06.880
So essentially, we just cheated

00:11:06.880 --> 00:11:08.479
and analyzed all CRAN packages.

00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:10.479
And so what we did is,

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
rank compared to everything else.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:14.880
So now we can figure out,

00:11:14.880 --> 00:11:16.159
is 10 a big number?

00:11:16.159 --> 00:11:17.200
You know, if we go,

00:11:17.200 --> 00:11:18.159
well, 10 is a big number,

00:11:18.159 --> 00:11:19.520
but every single package in CRAN

00:11:19.520 --> 00:11:20.239
is more than 10,

00:11:20.799 --> 00:11:21.840
it's a bit of a waste of time,

00:11:21.840 --> 00:11:22.799
we're all honest.

00:11:22.799 --> 00:11:23.200
You know, again,

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:24.960
we're trying to get some detail.

00:11:24.960 --> 00:11:25.840
So, you know,

00:11:26.559 --> 00:11:27.440
this is the graph.

00:11:28.080 --> 00:11:29.840
So, you know,

00:11:31.119 --> 00:11:32.960
Quantile 1 has only got one dependency.

00:11:32.960 --> 00:11:35.840
We stripped off R and base packages, right?

00:11:35.840 --> 00:11:37.280
But 25% of packages

00:11:37.280 --> 00:11:38.400
don't have a single dependency

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:39.919
when you get rid of the obvious ones.

00:11:41.039 --> 00:11:42.479
50% have three dependencies,

00:11:42.479 --> 00:11:44.159
and then the maximum is 49,

00:11:44.159 --> 00:11:46.000
which is quite a lot of dependencies.

00:11:48.239 --> 00:11:48.880
And there's a little bit

00:11:48.880 --> 00:11:50.159
of survivorship bias,

00:11:50.159 --> 00:11:54.000
because CRAN can sometimes be strict.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:54.880
And so essentially,

00:11:54.880 --> 00:11:56.080
if a package fails,

00:11:56.080 --> 00:11:57.359
it gets kicked off.

00:11:57.359 --> 00:11:58.880
So I'm guessing that any package

00:11:58.880 --> 00:12:00.159
with lots of dependencies

00:12:00.960 --> 00:12:01.919
from a long time ago

00:12:01.919 --> 00:12:03.119
has probably been removed

00:12:03.119 --> 00:12:04.159
if they're not updating,

00:12:04.159 --> 00:12:05.679
because you're sort of getting rid of that.

00:12:05.679 --> 00:12:06.880
So that's why you've got that long tail.

00:12:07.440 --> 00:12:08.000
But essentially,

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:09.200
we just map the ECDF,

00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:11.359
empirical CDF,

00:12:11.359 --> 00:12:13.359
so convert that to a probability,

00:12:13.359 --> 00:12:14.640
oh, it's got between zero and one.

00:12:15.760 --> 00:12:17.280
We do the same with code base size.

00:12:18.080 --> 00:12:19.440
So, you know, all of CRAN,

00:12:19.440 --> 00:12:21.119
you know, the average,

00:12:21.119 --> 00:12:23.599
the median number is 600 lines of code.

00:12:24.159 --> 00:12:25.599
The maximum is 100,000,

00:12:25.599 --> 00:12:27.440
which seems like a big number to me,

00:12:27.440 --> 00:12:28.400
if we're going back down there.

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:30.479
And again, we just map it

00:12:30.479 --> 00:12:32.239
to the ECDF,

00:12:32.239 --> 00:12:33.919
empirical distribution.

00:12:33.919 --> 00:12:35.280
Again, I thought far too long

00:12:35.280 --> 00:12:36.400
about log transformations

00:12:36.400 --> 00:12:37.440
and everything else,

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:38.479
whereas if you just rank it,

00:12:39.200 --> 00:12:40.320
things just sort of come out,

00:12:40.320 --> 00:12:41.760
and that's what you're trying to capture.

00:12:44.159 --> 00:12:46.559
So, oh, okay.

00:12:48.080 --> 00:12:49.840
So moving to R.

00:12:52.719 --> 00:12:53.760
We work with lots of companies,

00:12:53.760 --> 00:12:54.719
and one of the problems is

00:12:54.719 --> 00:12:56.080
they set up R,

00:12:56.080 --> 00:12:57.520
they set up whatever, Connect,

00:12:58.719 --> 00:12:59.919
and people in this audience

00:12:59.919 --> 00:13:01.520
will be stunned to realize this.

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:02.479
Then they don't touch it

00:13:02.479 --> 00:13:03.679
for the next four years,

00:13:03.679 --> 00:13:05.200
and everything just, you know,

00:13:05.200 --> 00:13:06.159
you've got this set up,

00:13:06.159 --> 00:13:07.440
and it just sort of sits there.

00:13:08.159 --> 00:13:08.960
And that's sort of similar

00:13:08.960 --> 00:13:10.000
with package validation.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:11.440
Someone sat and thought about it,

00:13:12.880 --> 00:13:14.000
but we've gone to a conference,

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:15.520
and we're hearing about lots of cool things.

00:13:15.520 --> 00:13:16.880
You need to try and build in procedures

00:13:16.880 --> 00:13:18.719
of how do I get new things

00:13:18.719 --> 00:13:20.640
in my organization, okay?

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:22.799
And so there's a URL,

00:13:22.799 --> 00:13:23.679
and I'll put the URL,

00:13:23.679 --> 00:13:25.280
or a QR code at the end.

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:26.960
So there's a dashboard essentially of,

00:13:26.960 --> 00:13:29.280
it's just showing all the packages,

00:13:29.280 --> 00:13:30.000
and you can just sort of

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:30.880
look at all these scores

00:13:30.880 --> 00:13:31.919
and figure it out.

00:13:31.919 --> 00:13:33.039
Just now it's static

00:13:33.039 --> 00:13:34.239
with 1,000 packages,

00:13:34.239 --> 00:13:36.080
but in the next sort of four to six weeks,

00:13:36.640 --> 00:13:37.679
we're planning on, you know,

00:13:37.679 --> 00:13:39.840
all of CRAN, CI, CD, job,

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:40.960
pushing things up to date,

00:13:40.960 --> 00:13:41.840
you know, so it's all open.

00:13:43.039 --> 00:13:44.320
So there's a dashboard overview

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:45.760
of all the packages, okay?

00:13:45.760 --> 00:13:47.200
So here's 1,000.

00:13:47.200 --> 00:13:49.679
We've got a histogram of,

00:13:49.679 --> 00:13:51.119
you know, in this collection,

00:13:51.119 --> 00:13:52.559
it's got 1,000 packages,

00:13:52.559 --> 00:13:54.080
so we've got an overall score,

00:13:54.080 --> 00:13:54.960
you know, so it ranges up

00:13:54.960 --> 00:13:56.159
from 0.5 to one.

00:13:57.760 --> 00:13:59.440
It turns out that we typically use,

00:13:59.440 --> 00:13:59.760
you know,

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:01.679
whilst this is a bit flippant

00:14:01.679 --> 00:14:03.359
about what packages we use,

00:14:03.359 --> 00:14:05.200
intuitively we do the right thing.

00:14:05.200 --> 00:14:06.799
You know, we might not follow a process,

00:14:07.359 --> 00:14:10.400
but even an academic as me at times

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:11.359
at least tries to make sure

00:14:11.359 --> 00:14:12.400
that the package is working

00:14:12.400 --> 00:14:13.280
and it's sensible,

00:14:13.280 --> 00:14:15.280
you know, so we don't just choose things

00:14:15.280 --> 00:14:16.000
at random,

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:17.119
but we need to show a process.

00:14:18.080 --> 00:14:20.239
We've got a score breakdown, okay?

00:14:20.239 --> 00:14:22.719
So we split this up into documentation,

00:14:22.719 --> 00:14:24.799
code, maintenance, popularity,

00:14:24.799 --> 00:14:25.679
and then you can wait

00:14:25.679 --> 00:14:26.880
however you'd like to wait.

00:14:26.880 --> 00:14:28.880
So in this analysis,

00:14:28.880 --> 00:14:29.919
code is weighted a bit more

00:14:29.919 --> 00:14:30.880
than documentation

00:14:30.880 --> 00:14:32.400
because we think code's more important,

00:14:32.400 --> 00:14:34.960
but you can change it, okay?

00:14:34.960 --> 00:14:36.080
We've got the bit about high,

00:14:37.119 --> 00:14:38.719
those red lines, high risk.

00:14:38.719 --> 00:14:40.320
So of these 1,000 packages,

00:14:40.320 --> 00:14:41.440
there's one that's been flagged

00:14:41.440 --> 00:14:43.359
with a security vulnerability, okay?

00:14:43.359 --> 00:14:44.640
So then you might think of,

00:14:44.640 --> 00:14:46.080
so security vulnerability,

00:14:46.080 --> 00:14:47.679
what do you want to do about it?

00:14:47.679 --> 00:14:49.440
And it's not of can't use it,

00:14:49.440 --> 00:14:50.880
it's about someone going in and going,

00:14:50.880 --> 00:14:52.000
I understand the risk,

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:52.960
I'm okay with that risk,

00:14:52.960 --> 00:14:54.559
or I'm not okay with that risk.

00:14:54.559 --> 00:14:55.919
So it's not of we can't use it,

00:14:55.919 --> 00:14:58.640
it's should I use it, right?

00:15:00.159 --> 00:15:01.440
You can do package drill then.

00:15:03.599 --> 00:15:05.760
So, you know, you get all the scores

00:15:05.760 --> 00:15:07.679
and all the parametrics

00:15:07.679 --> 00:15:08.400
that we've talked about.

00:15:09.679 --> 00:15:11.119
You can see what's good, what's bad.

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:14.559
You can do a comparison with other packages

00:15:14.559 --> 00:15:15.840
for a particular, you know,

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:16.960
how does .whisker,

00:15:16.960 --> 00:15:18.799
I have no idea what .whisker does,

00:15:18.799 --> 00:15:19.919
and it was on my laptop

00:15:19.919 --> 00:15:21.359
and I installed it and must have run it,

00:15:21.359 --> 00:15:24.320
but so, yeah, what it does, so that's good.

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:25.440
We can record decisions.

00:15:26.080 --> 00:15:28.799
So that's important if you're in an organization

00:15:28.799 --> 00:15:31.200
where you need to show what you're doing.

00:15:31.200 --> 00:15:33.520
So I have chosen to use this package.

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:34.799
There's a security vulnerability,

00:15:34.799 --> 00:15:36.000
but I'm okay with the risk.

00:15:36.799 --> 00:15:37.919
And sometimes you think,

00:15:37.919 --> 00:15:38.880
you couldn't possibly do that,

00:15:38.880 --> 00:15:40.080
that happens all the time.

00:15:40.080 --> 00:15:41.840
You know, you've taken,

00:15:41.840 --> 00:15:42.719
you've assessed the risk

00:15:42.719 --> 00:15:44.159
and you think that risk is okay.

00:15:44.719 --> 00:15:45.760
But many organizations,

00:15:45.760 --> 00:15:47.599
you have to make sure you can record that risk

00:15:47.599 --> 00:15:49.359
to say, yes, Colin came along,

00:15:49.359 --> 00:15:50.559
he looked at that and he said,

00:15:50.559 --> 00:15:52.799
it's okay because of these reasons, right?

00:15:52.799 --> 00:15:54.000
You know, the reasons could be,

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:54.799
it's a vulnerability,

00:15:54.799 --> 00:15:56.640
but the package is only used internally.

00:15:56.640 --> 00:15:58.640
It can't access anything external.

00:15:58.640 --> 00:15:59.760
Fine, that seems okay.

00:16:00.799 --> 00:16:04.880
So summary, a lot of thought goes a long way.

00:16:04.880 --> 00:16:07.840
So the dashboard, the QR code,

00:16:08.880 --> 00:16:10.159
that will take you to, you know,

00:16:10.159 --> 00:16:12.000
the idea next maybe four or six weeks,

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:13.280
you would have all the packages in CRAN.

00:16:13.280 --> 00:16:14.640
So if you want to see a package,

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:15.840
you can have a look,

00:16:15.840 --> 00:16:18.080
help win that argument with IT, okay?

00:16:19.280 --> 00:16:22.400
We're starting to do sort of rapid GXP type environments.

00:16:22.400 --> 00:16:23.760
So if you're in that sort of space,

00:16:23.760 --> 00:16:24.719
please come and talk to me.

00:16:25.359 --> 00:16:28.080
Also do another service called diffify.com,

00:16:28.080 --> 00:16:29.359
which go to that URL,

00:16:29.359 --> 00:16:31.039
basically type in any package you want

00:16:31.039 --> 00:16:32.320
and it will show you what functions

00:16:32.320 --> 00:16:33.840
have changed between any versions.

00:16:33.840 --> 00:16:34.960
So you can mess a bit with that

00:16:34.960 --> 00:16:36.320
and that's just out there.

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:37.760
So thank you very much

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:39.039
and happy to take questions.

00:16:46.840 --> 00:16:51.599
Thank you so much, Colin.

00:16:51.599 --> 00:16:53.359
It was very interesting to hear

00:16:53.359 --> 00:16:55.520
about all these different metrics.

00:16:59.200 --> 00:17:00.479
From the questions from Slido,

00:17:00.479 --> 00:17:02.719
we have, when a measure becomes a target,

00:17:02.719 --> 00:17:04.640
it ceases to be a good measure.

00:17:05.280 --> 00:17:07.920
As we move towards objective measures of packages,

00:17:07.920 --> 00:17:09.920
do you anticipate packages evolving

00:17:09.920 --> 00:17:11.280
to be ranked higher

00:17:11.280 --> 00:17:13.040
without necessarily improvements

00:17:13.040 --> 00:17:14.160
to overall quality?

00:17:15.119 --> 00:17:16.959
So, yes.

00:17:18.400 --> 00:17:20.239
So in some cases of a package,

00:17:20.239 --> 00:17:21.040
so one of the metrics is,

00:17:21.040 --> 00:17:23.839
does it have a source URL?

00:17:23.839 --> 00:17:25.680
GitHub, GitLab, Atlassian, whatever you want.

00:17:26.319 --> 00:17:27.760
And if an author thought,

00:17:27.760 --> 00:17:29.040
oh, I'm getting a zero here

00:17:29.040 --> 00:17:30.319
because it's not in source control,

00:17:30.319 --> 00:17:31.599
I think we could all agree of,

00:17:31.599 --> 00:17:32.880
it's a good push, right?

00:17:32.880 --> 00:17:34.479
You know, they're now hitting a target,

00:17:34.479 --> 00:17:35.920
but I think we can all agree it's a good target.

00:17:36.560 --> 00:17:38.319
And you go, oh, but they might then write tests

00:17:38.319 --> 00:17:39.439
that aren't very good.

00:17:39.439 --> 00:17:40.880
It's like, they could.

00:17:41.680 --> 00:17:43.439
But who could be bothered with that?

00:17:43.439 --> 00:17:45.199
You know, in the grand scheme of things,

00:17:45.199 --> 00:17:47.119
could you really be bothered

00:17:47.119 --> 00:17:48.560
to go to the effort

00:17:48.560 --> 00:17:50.880
to get 100% test coverage

00:17:51.760 --> 00:17:53.839
that anyone with more than two seconds

00:17:53.839 --> 00:17:55.839
worth of looking at your code would go,

00:17:56.400 --> 00:17:58.160
that's rubbish, right?

00:17:58.160 --> 00:17:59.920
You know, so it could theoretically happen,

00:17:59.920 --> 00:18:01.920
but I just don't fundamentally believe they will.

00:18:02.479 --> 00:18:04.079
And if it did, it would be spotted.

00:18:04.079 --> 00:18:04.880
Because again,

00:18:05.439 --> 00:18:07.599
we don't just install packages at random,

00:18:07.599 --> 00:18:09.359
you know, whereas I was making flipping jokes.

00:18:10.319 --> 00:18:13.199
We do think about that package is solving this problem,

00:18:13.199 --> 00:18:14.800
and it's been written by someone I respect,

00:18:14.800 --> 00:18:16.000
and I'm installing it and using it.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:17.680
And we're doing it intuitively,

00:18:17.680 --> 00:18:18.959
and this is just formalizing that.

00:18:18.959 --> 00:18:20.640
All right, lovely.

00:18:21.280 --> 00:18:23.520
This is a short question

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:24.880
that I'll rephrase a little bit.

00:18:25.920 --> 00:18:28.079
Can we treat tidyverse as a single dependency?

00:18:30.959 --> 00:18:33.920
So the way we do it is if some,

00:18:33.920 --> 00:18:35.439
so when we're working with pharmaceutical companies,

00:18:35.439 --> 00:18:36.800
if they say, we only want tidyverse,

00:18:36.800 --> 00:18:37.760
we go, that's fine.

00:18:37.760 --> 00:18:39.920
We work the dependencies of the dependencies.

00:18:40.479 --> 00:18:43.520
So that will end up being 100, 200 packages.

00:18:44.239 --> 00:18:46.239
And then it's, again, it's up to,

00:18:46.239 --> 00:18:47.359
you know, we would then say,

00:18:47.359 --> 00:18:49.680
you should think about all those packages,

00:18:49.680 --> 00:18:50.880
because they've all been used.

00:18:50.880 --> 00:18:52.160
But, you know, you can do what you want.

00:18:52.959 --> 00:18:55.119
Typically for a small analysis,

00:18:55.119 --> 00:18:57.839
you know, so a bit of data cleaning,

00:18:57.839 --> 00:19:00.079
a bit of ggplotting,

00:19:00.079 --> 00:19:01.680
a little bit of stats,

00:19:01.680 --> 00:19:05.119
you're ending up with about 500 packages from the start.

00:19:05.119 --> 00:19:06.640
You know, that's a sort of baseline

00:19:06.800 --> 00:19:07.839
and sort of hand-wavy things.

